outgoing_paragraph_urls.anchor_text: Data Science is filled with various tools

all_paragraphs: The domain of Data Science brings with itself a variety of scientific tools, processes, algorithms, and knowledge extraction systems from structured and unstructured data alike, for identifying meaningful patterns in it.

Data Science is a rapidly growing industry and is currently one of the most desirable domains of this decade to work in. This translates to thousands of people with varying levels of Data Science-related skills actively trying to get into the world of Data Science. If you’re also passionate to learn about what Data Science has to offer and are looking to acquire new skills to add to your portfolio, then look no further.

Throughout this article, we will go through a handful of GitHub repositories that highlight the capabilities of Data Science with their range of diverse projects for a range of use cases. Open-source projects like these are perfect for studying the various aspects of Data Science while giving you the option to tinker with them so that once you feel confident, you can build one of your own.
Data really powers everything that we do.

GitHub is undoubtedly one of the best places to familiarize yourself with open-source code for not just Data Science but any technology. Being a fairly widespread domain, Data Science is filled with various tools, frameworks, techniques, and algorithms to extract insightful knowledge from the data.

The projects covered in this section do an amazing job of portraying how Data Science can be deployed in various walks of life and how you can easily get the information you need from it. But before digging into this, check out the12 Data Science Projects Ideas for Beginners and Experts.

Short for A Lite BERT(Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers), ALBERT is a lightweight BERT that was designed to achieve better performance by overcoming the memory limitations of a full-scale BERT. ALBERT does this by using significantly fewer parameters than regular BERT.

While Google’s BERT allows anyone to train their own models with high accuracy, ALBERT has gone a step ahead in achieving higher performance yields with only 10% of the parameters. BERT and ALBERT both allow you to train your models on either a GPU or a TPU. If any of your tasks require working with an NLP, we highly suggest you give ALBERT a try to see the performance gains for yourself.

If artistic projects are your thing, we recommend giving Tiler a shot. Tiler is a fun and exciting open-source project that is built using Python and allows anyone to create interesting and unique images. The way this project works is that it offers you a range of shapes in different colors that are rotated at various angles to create more complex images. All you have to do is pass the desired image that you want to be tiled as an argument and let Tiler work its magic. Tiler also has a bunch of other arguments that you can use to fine-tune your final image.

Tiler provides many different kinds of shapes out-of-the-box, such as waves, cross-stitches, circles, lego, hearts, and much more in multiple colors. Tiler is designed with flexibility in mind as it comes with the option to let its users create their own tiles of various colors if they’re feeling extra creative.

This Data Science GitHub repo focuses on providing a variety of Pre-Trained Models for a range of problems. For the uninitiated, pre-trained models are the lifeline of Transfer Learning, where people can use someone else’s model with minor tinkering that has been trained on a similar problem.

Pre-Trained Models are vital to keeping the training costs to a minimum as they can help you don’t need to spend on any dedicated training hardware(GPUs) while also helping you cut down on the overall time spent.

The repo is home to research papers on over a hundred models that can help you get a deeper understanding of the problems and their proposed solutions. The repo also contains an infographic to represent the relationships between these PLMs.

If you were ever intrigued by how megacorporations moved their data around from one site to another in real-time, this project might be able to give you a peek at the secret. Open-sourced about a year ago and now adopted by the Apache Software Foundation, TubeMQ is an enterprise-grade distributed messaging queue(MQ) system that is designed to deliver high-performance storage and transmission of extremely large volumes of data.

TubeMQ can help organizations gain the upper hand by offering several key benefits in terms of throughput, latency, stability, performance, and cost while maintaining full scalability. Other notable features of this project include a feature-rich dashboard, authentication and authorization, support for Big Data and streaming ecosystem, compatible with transport protocols such as TCP and SSL, an efficient push and pull consumption model, and much more.

The modern world is deeply connected to the internet, where the word “Privacy” has lost its meaning and is just a myth now. Every application or service that you use is in some way tracking your every move to profile you and to offer you better services and recommendations before you even ask for it.

DeepPrivacy is one such GitHub project that aims to automatically anonymize faces in images. DeepPrivacy uses Generative Adversarial Network(GAN) to achieve face anonymization by using bounding boxes to identify sensitive areas and sparse pose information to guide the network in various scenarios. The project uses the best-in-class detection models, Mask-R-CNN for generating sparse pose information, and DSFD for face identification. If you’re interested in studying the research paper for DeepPrivacy, you can also do so from the GitHub repo.

This Data Science project is a great step in solving the major problem of targeting the right recommendation or search result to users by predicting their Click Through Rate(CTR). The DeepCTR project provides access to many easy-to-use, modular, and extensible Deep Learning models with loads of core component layers that you can use to build custom models. Some of the many supported models include:
While this variant of DeepCTR may not seem like everyone’s cup of tea due to its TensorFlow implementation, there’s also DeepCTR-Torch, which uses the PyTorch implementation for this project.

Face Recognition tools can be used with facial data from a person’s image to analyze and extract many key bits of information, such as gender, age, and more. Present-day tools leveraging the latest technologies can recognize faces from videos as well as images. Alexandre Attia’s modern face recognition tool utilizes Deep Learning and is powered by the Histogram of Oriented Gradients method. A more detailed list of steps used by this face recognition tool include:
● Finding faces in an image using the HOG algorithm to get a basic representation of the facial structure
● Transformations like shearing, rotation, scaling and so, to center the eyes and mouth
● Encoding of the detected face using Deep Learning with a trained Neural Net
● And lastly, using a classifier(LVM or any other) to find the person in the database with the closest match to the test image

Built using Python, this project provides a hands-on experience of how a Natural Language Processing(NLP) system works for text mining. The project has been demoed on a 2019 report by the Mexican Government and includes a number of activities to cleanly extract text from the report and visualize it later on.
To achieve this, the project uses multiple Python libraries. A brief explanation about each library is explained below:
● PyPDF2: a highly customizable library used for reliably extracting clean text from PDFs
● spaCy: a blazing-fast library for real-world Natural Language Processing workloads
● NumPy: providing the necessary computational power for the project
● pandas: for extracting and analyzing valuable insights from the datasets
● matplotlib: for creating stunning and insightful data visualizations
● seaborn: for more precise control over graphs and plots built with matplotlib
● geopandas: useful for working with spatial databases and plotting visually-appealing geomaps

This Data Science project is aimed towards application security and the target users for this are mostly the Malware Analysts and Cybersecurity experts. The StringSifter project leverages the power of the strings program in Python and Machine Learning to make it easier to find a range of hidden strings in program binaries of all sizes.

Often used with malicious intent, these hidden strings can be found with almost zero hassle by providing them as input to the StringSifter program. Once the list is fed to the program, it then sifts deep into the binary to report back any relevant findings of them to the analysts. Being an easy to use tool, security experts can effortlessly integrate StringSifter into their existing malware analysis stack. Users also have the option to use StringSifter with a Docker image as all the required command-line utilities are readily available.

Another project from the developer who brought us the Face Recognition project in this list, this rating prediction system tries to predict movie ratings for movies on IMDb before the movie is even released. Backed by Machine Learning, the ProjectMovieRating project tries to do this in three parts explained below:
● Part 1: It tries to parse data such as cast information, awards, directors, genres, budgets, and more from IMDb and the numbers website for target movie
● Part 2: It then tries to analyze the data to identify any correlation between the variables from part 1.
● Part 3: At the final step, the project uses the Machine Learning algorithm Random Forests to predict the IMDb rating of the movie

Data Science has already become a highly competitive domain, which requires constantly staying up-to-date about the latest and the best techniques to get the job done. To stay on top of the competition, you need to up your game. Theoretical education is fine and all, but if you’re not putting that knowledge to solve real-world problems, it’ll not be of any use to you.

In this write-up, we tried to cover a range of Data Science projects on GitHub involving some fun and in-demand topics that try to provide efficient solutions to some challenging real-world problems in multiple domains. Do we have our fingers crossed that these projects will inspire you to dabble in Data Science to create your own version of a solution, or maybe a fun project, perhaps?
Note: To eliminate problems of different kinds, I want to alert you to the fact this article represent just my personal opinion I want to share, and you possess every right to disagree with it.
If you have more suggestions, I’d love to hear about them.
